'''Harriet Fasenfest''' (born 1953)<ref name="NY">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/06/garden/06root.html?pagewanted=2 |title=Food Storage As Grandma Knew It |last=Tortorello |first=Michael |date=5 November 2008 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> is an American writer, urban gardener, and [[food preservation]] educator in [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]. A former owner/operator of several restaurants and cafes, she uses the term "[[wikt:householding|householding]]" when referring to the practice of home food growing, canning and storage.<ref name="live"/><ref name="choice">{{cite web |url=http://www.culinate.com/mix/dinner_guest/what_is_householding |title=What is Householding? Making the choice to stay home |last=Fasenfest |first=Harriet |date=12 March 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |publisher=Culinate.com}}</ref> She published her first book, ''A Householder's Guide to the Universe'', in 2010.
==Biography== Fasenfest was born and raised in [[Bronx, New York]]. She moved to the Northwest in 1978<ref name="cul">{{cite web |url=http://www.culinate.com/mix/dinner_guest?author=4457 |title=Posts by Harriet Fasenfest |publisher=Culinate |year=2010 |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> where she owned and operated the Bertie Lou's and Harriet's Eat Now cafes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseagreen.com/authors/harriet_fasenfest/ |title=Our Chelsea Green Authors : Harriet Fasenfest |publisher=Chelsea Green Publishing |year=2011 |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref><ref name="preserve">{{cite web |url=http://www.portlandpreserve.com/about2.html |title=About Us |publisher=Preserve |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref> In 1990 she went back to traveling the country, married, moved back to California, and then moved to Georgia in 1992. While there, she began working with [[Habitat for Humanity|Habitat for Humanity International]]. In 1997 Fasenfest returned to Portland to work as director of the Performance Salon Series at North Portland's North Star Ballroom, an events arena which combined art and performance with [[Activism|social activism]], and in 2000 opened her last cafe, Groundswell.<ref name="ore">{{cite web |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/visualarts/2007/10/last_thursday_part_iii.html |title=Harriet Fasenfest: The View From Here |last=Row |first=D.K. |date=17 November 2000 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |work=The Oregonian}}</ref>
In 2004 she transformed her backyard in Northern Portland into a producing garden. She grows produce with an eye to [[home canning]] and storing,<ref name="oregon">{{cite web |url=http://www.oregonhomemagazine.com/garden/709-earthly-delights-urban-farmers |title=Harvest Swoon: An expert householder's bountiful garden |last=Foley |first=Margaret |date=5 July 2011 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |work=Oregan Home Magazine|pages=1&ndash;2}}</ref> and teaches classes in food preservation and backyard gardening.<ref name="city">{{cite web |url=http://www.cityfarmer.info/2010/11/02/the-householders-guide-to-the-universe/ |title=The Householders Guide To The Universe |year=2010 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |publisher=City Farmer News}}</ref> She is the co-owner of Preserve, an educational center for home gardening and food preservation,<ref name="preserve"/> and creator of the www.portlandpreserve.com website,<ref name="NY"/> on which she writes a blog called ''The Householder's Grab Bag''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ahouseholdersguide.portlandpreserve.com/ |title=The Householder's Grab Bag: A repository of reflections on these curious times |year=2010 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |publisher=portlandpreserve.com}}</ref> She also blogs for Culinate.com.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culinate.com/mix/dinner_guest?author=4457 |title=Posts by Harriet Fasenfest |publisher=Culinate |year=2011 |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref>
Fasenfest regards home food preservation as a political and economic statement. She uses the term "[[wikt:householding|householding]]" rather than "[[homemaking]]" or "[[home economics]]" to describe her work.<ref name="live"/><ref name="choice"/> She published her views on home gardening and food preservation in ''A Householder's Guide to the Universe: A Calendar of Basics for the Home and Beyond''. The book is organized by month and season.<ref name="city"/>
She lives in Portland, Oregon <ref name="live">{{cite web |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/O/index.ssf/2009/03/a_northeast_portland_woman_hom.html |title=A Northeast Portland woman homes in on simpler solutions |work=[[The Oregonian]] |last=Verzemnieks |first=Inara |date=7 March 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2011}}</ref>
