{{about|the German-Australian [[nine-pin bowling]] game||Kegel (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Kegeln-Kugel.jpg|right|thumb|Ninepin bowling pins and ball]]
'''{{Lang|de|Kegel}}''', or {{lang|de|kegeln}}, (German for "[[wikt:skittle|skittle]]", [[Skittles (sport)|skittles]]) is a German [[bowling]] game played in Australia, in which a player rolls a wooden or plastic ball along a smooth, hard indoor lane (German: ''{{Lang|de|Kegelbahn}}'', [[bowling alley]]).<ref>[http://www.tanundakegelclub.8m.com/history.htm The Official Home Page of the Tanunda Kegel Club]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707070316/http://www.tanundakegelclub.8m.com/history.htm |date=July 7, 2011 }}</ref> The object of the game is to knock down the nine kegels at the other end of the lane. Kegel is based on the traditional German game of [[nine-pin bowling]] and is therefore closely related to both skittles and [[ten-pin bowling]]. It was introduced to [[South Australia]] by [[German settlement in Australia|German settlers]] in the 19th century and remains popular in areas in which many German people settled, such as the [[Barossa Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teachers.ash.org.au/dnutting/germanaustralia/e/traditions.htm|title=German Traditions, Influences and Leisure Activities|accessdate=June 26, 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817002059/http://teachers.ash.org.au/dnutting/germanaustralia/e/traditions.htm|archivedate=August 17, 2007}}</ref>

